    "narrative": "Today\u2019s lineup for Ghost Ride the WHIP centers on exploiting high-leverage speed opportunities and favorable matchups against moderate pitching. **Jazz Chisholm Jr.** headlines our starters with an elite 73.62 rating; his matchup against Leiter is bolstered by an ideal environment for his baserunning profile, as Leiter\u2019s 94% stolen base allowance and relatively slow delivery time provide the perfect setup for **Jazz Chisholm Jr.** to capitalize on our league\u2019s premium on stolen bases. **Josh Naylor** also projects strongly at 69.00, benefiting from a favorable wind forecast and a manageable 4.50 xERA from Prielipp, which mitigates the minor penalty incurred by his handedness. Meanwhile, **Seiya Suzuki** remains a reliable start at 63.92, largely due to a lucrative matchup against V\u00e1squez, whose 5.43 xERA allows **Seiya Suzuki** to transcend his park-factor adjustment.\n\nThe decision to start **Jose Caballero** at 50.13, despite his spot at the bottom of the order, was driven by our organizational priority on speed; even with a platoon disadvantage against Leiter, his utility in stealing bases against the pitcher\u2019s slow delivery outweighed the marginal gains offered by other options. **Trevor Story** presented the most difficult bench decision, ultimately landing in the UTIL spot with a 53.78 score. He narrowly edged out our depth pieces because his BvP metrics and the projected 88% success rate against Cease's delivery tempo made him a statistically superior play to keep in the lineup despite the tough matchup against a premier arm. While players like **Corbin Carroll**, **James Wood**, **Tyler Soderstrom**, and **Vinnie Pasquantino** remain sidelined by off-days, we are keeping a close watch on the status of **Mickey Moniak**, **Austin Riley**, **Giancarlo Stanton**, **Brice Turang**, **Gabriel Moreno**, **Max Muncy**, **Luis Campusano**, **Dalton Rushing**, **Zach McKinstry**, **Kyle Karros**, **Carson Williams**, and **